[src:curry-language/backtracking] The classic textbook example of the use of backtracking is the eight queens puzzle, that asks for all arrangements of eight chess queens on a standard chessboard so that no queen attacks any other.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] In the common backtracking approach, the partial candidates are arrangements of *k* queens in the first *k* rows of the board, all in different rows and columns.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] Any partial solution that contains two mutually attacking queens can be abandoned.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] Backtracking can be applied only for problems which admit the concept of a "partial candidate solution" and a relatively quick test of whether it can possibly be completed to a valid solution.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] It is useless, for example, for locating a given value in an unordered table.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] When it is applicable, however, backtracking is often much faster than brute-force enumeration of all complete candidates, since it can eliminate many candidates with a single test.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] Backtracking is an important tool for solving constraint satisfaction problems, such as crosswords, verbal arithmetic, Sudoku, and many other puzzles.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] It is often the most convenient technique for parsing, for the knapsack problem and other combinatorial optimization problems.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] It is also the program execution strategy used in the programming languages Icon, Planner and Prolog.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] Backtracking depends on user-given "black box procedures" that define the problem to be solved, the nature of the partial candidates, and how they are extended into complete candidates.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] It is therefore a metaheuristic rather than a specific algorithm – although, unlike many other meta-heuristics, it is guaranteed to find all solutions to a finite problem in a bounded amount of time.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The term "backtrack" was coined by American mathematician D.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The pioneer string-processing language SNOBOL (1962) may have been the first to provide a built-in general backtracking facility.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The backtracking algorithm enumerates a set of *partial candidates* that, in principle, could be *completed* in various ways to give all the possible solutions to the given problem.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The backtracking algorithm traverses this search tree recursively, from the root down, in depth-first order.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] At each node *c*, the algorithm checks whether *c* can be completed to a valid solution.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] If it cannot, the whole sub-tree rooted at *c* is skipped (*pruned*).
[src:curry-language/backtracking] Otherwise, the algorithm (1) checks whether *c* itself is a valid solution, and if so reports it to the user; and (2) recursively enumerates all sub-trees of *c*.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The two tests and the children of each node are defined by user-given procedures.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] Therefore, the *actual search tree* that is traversed by the algorithm is only a part of the potential tree.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The total cost of the algorithm is the number of nodes of the actual tree times the cost of obtaining and processing each node.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] This fact should be considered when choosing the potential search tree and implementing the pruning test.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] In order to apply backtracking to a specific class of problems, one must provide the data *P* for the particular instance of the problem that is to be solved, and six procedural parameters, *root*, *reject*, *accept*, *first*, *next*, and *output*.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] *reject*(*P*,*c*): return *true* only if the partial candidate *c* is not worth completing.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] *accept*(*P*,*c*): return *true* if *c* is a solution of *P*, and *false* otherwise.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] *first*(*P*,*c*): generate the first extension of candidate *c*.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] *next*(*P*,*s*): generate the next alternative extension of a candidate, after the extension *s*.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] *output*(*P*,*c*): use the solution *c* of *P*, as appropriate to the application.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The *reject* procedure should be a Boolean-valued function that returns *true* only if it is certain that no possible extension of *c* is a valid solution for *P*.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] If the procedure cannot reach a definite conclusion, it should return *false*.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] An incorrect *true* result may cause the *backtrack* procedure to miss some valid solutions.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The procedure may assume that *reject*(*P*,*t*) returned *false* for every ancestor *t* of *c* in the search tree.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] On the other hand, the efficiency of the backtracking algorithm depends on *reject* returning *true* for candidates that are as close to the root as possible.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] If *reject* always returns *false*, the algorithm will still find all solutions, but it will be equivalent to a brute-force search.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The *accept* procedure should return *true* if *c* is a complete and valid solution for the problem instance *P*, and *false* otherwise.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] It may assume that the partial candidate *c* and all its ancestors in the tree have passed the *reject* test.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The general pseudo-code above does not assume that the valid solutions are always leaves of the potential search tree.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] In other words, it admits the possibility that a valid solution for *P* can be further extended to yield other valid solutions.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The *first* and *next* procedures are used by the backtracking algorithm to enumerate the children of a node *c* of the tree, that is, the candidates that differ from *c* by a single extension step.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The call *first*(*P*,*c*) should yield the first child of *c*, in some order; and the call *next*(*P*,*s*) should return the next sibling of node *s*, in that order.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] Both functions should return a distinctive "NULL" candidate, if the requested child does not exist.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] Together, the *root*, *first*, and *next* functions define the set of partial candidates and the potential search tree.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] They should be chosen so that every solution of *P* occurs somewhere in the tree, and no partial candidate occurs more than once.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] Moreover, they should admit an efficient and effective *reject* predicate.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The pseudo-code above will call *output* for all candidates that are a solution to the given instance *P*.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The algorithm can be modified to stop after finding the first solution, or a specified number of solutions; or after testing a specified number of partial candidates, or after spending a given amount of CPU time.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The general constraint satisfaction problem consists in finding a list of integers *x* = (*x*[1], *x*[2], …, *x*[*n*]), each in some range {1, 2, …, *m*}, that satisfies some arbitrary constraint (Boolean function) *F*.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] For this class of problems, the instance data *P* would be the integers *m* and *n*, and the predicate *F*.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] In a typical backtracking solution to this problem, one could define a partial candidate as a list of integers *c* = (*c*[1], *c*[2], …, *c*[k]), for any *k* between 0 and *n*, that are to be assigned to the first *k* variables *x*[1], *x*[2], …, *x*[*k*].
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The root candidate would then be the empty list ().
[src:curry-language/backtracking] Here *length*(*c*) is the number of elements in the list *c*.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The call *reject*(*P*, *c*) should return *true* if the constraint *F* cannot be satisfied by any list of *n* integers that begins with the *k* elements of *c*.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] For backtracking to be effective, there must be a way to detect this situation, at least for some candidates *c*, without enumerating all those *m**n* − *k* *n*-tuples.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] In fact, *reject* needs only check those terms that do depend on *x*[*k*], since the terms that depend only on *x*[1], …, *x*[*k* − 1] will have been tested further up in the search tree.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] Assuming that *reject* is implemented as above, then *accept*(*P*, *c*) needs only check whether *c* is complete, that is, whether it has *n* elements.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] It is generally better to order the list of variables so that it begins with the most critical ones (i.e. the ones with fewest value options, or which have a greater impact on subsequent choices).
[src:curry-language/backtracking] One could also allow the *next* function to choose which variable should be assigned when extending a partial candidate, based on the values of the variables already assigned by it.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] Further improvements can be obtained by the technique of constraint propagation.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] In addition to retaining minimal recovery values used in backing up, backtracking implementations commonly keep a variable trail, to record value change history.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] An efficient implementation will avoid creating a variable trail entry between two successive changes when there is no choice point, as the backtracking will erase all of the changes as a single operation.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] An alternative to the variable trail is to keep a timestamp of when the last change was made to the variable.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] The timestamp is compared to the timestamp of a choice point.
[src:curry-language/backtracking] If the choice point has an associated time later than that of the variable, it is unnecessary to revert the variable when the choice point is backtracked, as it was changed before the choice point occurred.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] It is nearly a superset of Haskell but does not support all language extensions of Haskell.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] In contrast to Haskell, Curry has built-in support for non-deterministic computations involving search.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] A functional program is a set of functions defined by equations or rules.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] A functional computation consists of replacing subexpressions by equal (with regard to the function definitions) subexpressions until no more replacements (or reductions) are possible and a value or normal form is obtained.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] The expression “double 1” is replaced by 1+1.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] The latter can be replaced by 2 if we interpret the operator “+” to be defined by an infinite set of equations, e.g., 1+1 = 2, 1+2 = 3, etc.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] In this case, both derivations lead to the same result, a property known as confluence.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] This follows from a fundamental property of pure functional languages, termed referential transparency: the value of a computed result does not depend on the order or time of evaluation, due to the absence of side effects.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] This simplifies reasoning about, and maintaining, pure functional programs.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] As many functional languages like Haskell do, Curry supports the definition of algebraic data types by enumerating their constructors.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] More complex data structures can be obtained by recursive data types.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] We can define operations on recursive types by inductive definitions where pattern matching supports the convenient separation of the different cases.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Beyond its application for various programming tasks, the operation “++” is also useful to specify the behavior of other functions on lists.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Based on this specification, one can define a function that satisfies this specification by employing logic programming features.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Similarly to logic languages, functional logic languages provide search for solutions for existentially quantified variables.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] In contrast to pure logic languages, they support equation solving over nested functional expressions so that an equation like *ys*++[e] = [1,2,3] is solved by instantiating ys to the list [1,2] and *e* to the value 3.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Here, the symbol “=:=” is used for equational constraints in order to provide a syntactic distinction from defining equations.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Similarly, extra variables (i.e., variables not occurring in the left-hand side of the defining equation) are explicitly declared by “where … free” in order to provide some opportunities to detect bugs caused by typos.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] A conditional equation of the form *L* | *C* = *R* is applicable for reduction if its condition *C* has been solved.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] In contrast to purely functional languages where conditions are only evaluated to a Boolean value, functional logic languages support the solving of conditions by guessing values for the unknowns in the condition.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Narrowing as discussed in the next section is used to solve this kind of conditions.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Narrowing is a mechanism whereby a variable is bound to a value selected from among alternatives imposed by constraints.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Each possible value is tried in some order, with the remainder of the program invoked in each case to determine the validity of the binding.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Narrowing is an extension of logic programming, in that it performs a similar search, but can actually generate values as part of the search rather than just being limited to testing them.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Narrowing is useful because it allows a function to be treated as a relation: its value can be computed "in both directions".
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] The Curry examples of the previous section illustrate this.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] As noted in the prior section, narrowing can be thought of as reduction on a program term graph, and there are often many different ways (*strategies*) to reduce a given term graph.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Antoy et al. proved in the 1990s that a particular narrowing strategy, *needed narrowing*, is optimal in the sense of doing a number of reductions to get to a "normal form" corresponding to a solution that is minimal among sound and complete strategies.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Needed narrowing corresponds to a lazy strategy, in contrast to the SLD-resolution strategy of Prolog.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] The rule defining last shown above expresses the fact that the actual argument must match the result of narrowing the expression ys++[e].
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Haskell does not allow such a declaration since the pattern in the left-hand side contains a defined function (++).
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Such a pattern is also called *functional pattern*.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Functional patterns are enabled by the combined functional and logic features of Curry and support concise definitions of tasks requiring deep pattern matching in hierarchical data structures.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Since Curry is able to solve equations containing function calls with unknown values, its execution mechanism is based on non-deterministic computations, similarly to logic programming.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] This mechanism supports also the definition of *non-deterministic operations*, i.e., operations that delivers more than one result for a given input.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] The archetype of non-deterministic operations is the predefined infix operation ?, called *choice* operator, that returns one of its arguments.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Thus, the evaluation of the expression 0 ?
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Computing with non-deterministic operations and computing with free variables by narrowing has the same expressive power.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] The rules defining ? show an important feature of Curry: all rules are tried in order to evaluate some operation.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] returns any permutation of a given input list.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Due to the absence of side effects, a functional logic program can be executed with different strategies.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] To evaluate expressions, Curry uses a variant of the *needed narrowing* strategy which combines lazy evaluation with non-deterministic search strategies.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] In contrast to Prolog, which uses backtracking to search for solutions, Curry does not fix a particular search strategy.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] Hence, there are implementations of Curry, like KiCS2, where the user can easily select a search strategy, like depth-first search (backtracking), breadth-first search, iterative deepening, or parallel search.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] There are various implementations of Curry available.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] To support programming in Curry, there is a collection of Curry software packages, a Curry API search engine, a Curry language server providing IDE support, e.g., in Visual Studio Code, as well as various program documentation and analysis tools.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] John Alan Robinson discussed in his invited CL2000 paper the integration of functional programming with logic programming where he wrote: "It is inexplicable that the two idioms have been kept apart for so long within the computational logic repertory.
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] We need a single programming language in which both kinds of programming are possible and can be used in combination with each other." He surveyed different attempts and concluded that Curry is the "most promising one".
[src:curry-language/curry-programming-language] The textbook about principles and practice of programming languages contains a chapter on programming in Curry.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Haskell's semantics are historically based on those of the Miranda programming language, which served to focus the efforts of the initial Haskell working group.
[src:curry-language/haskell] The last formal specification of the language was made in July 2010, while the development of GHC continues to expand Haskell via language extensions.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Haskell is used in academia and industry.
[src:curry-language/haskell] As of May 2021, Haskell was the 28th most popular programming language by Google searches for tutorials, and made up less than 1% of active users on the GitHub source code repository.
[src:curry-language/haskell] After the release of Miranda by Research Software Ltd. in 1985, interest in lazy functional languages grew.
[src:curry-language/haskell] By 1987, more than a dozen non-strict, purely functional programming languages existed.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Miranda was the most widely used, but it was proprietary software.
[src:curry-language/haskell] At the conference on Functional Programming Languages and Computer Architecture (FPCA '87) in Portland, Oregon, there was a strong consensus that a committee be formed to define an open standard for such languages.
[src:curry-language/haskell] The committee's purpose was to consolidate existing functional languages into a common one to serve as a basis for future research in functional-language design.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Haskell was developed by a committee, attempting to bring together off-the-shelf solutions where possible.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Type classes were first proposed by Philip Wadler and Stephen Blott to address the ad hoc handling of equality types and arithmetic overloading in languages at the time.
[src:curry-language/haskell] In early versions of Haskell up until and including version 1.2, user interaction and input/output (IO) were handled by both streams-based and continuation-based mechanisms, which were widely considered unsatisfactory.
[src:curry-language/haskell] In version 1.3, monadic IO was introduced, along with the generalisation of type classes to higher kinds (type constructors).
[src:curry-language/haskell] Along with "do notation", which provides syntactic sugar for the `Monad` type class, this gave Haskell an effect system that maintained referential transparency and was convenient.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Another notable change in early versions was the moving of the "sequential evaluation" operation `seq` (which creates a data dependency between values, and is used in lazy languages to avoid excessive memory consumption) from a type class to a standard function to make refactoring more practical.
[src:curry-language/haskell] The first version of Haskell ("Haskell 1.0") was defined in 1990.
[src:curry-language/haskell] The committee's efforts resulted in a series of language definitions (1.0, 1.1, 1.2, 1.3, and 1.4).
[src:curry-language/haskell] In late 1997, the series culminated in *Haskell 98*, intended to specify a stable, minimal, portable version of the language and an accompanying standard library for teaching, and as a base for future extensions.
[src:curry-language/haskell] The committee expressly welcomed creating extensions and variants of Haskell 98 via adding and incorporating experimental features.
[src:curry-language/haskell] In February 1999, the Haskell 98 language standard was originally published as *The Haskell 98 Report*.
[src:curry-language/haskell] In January 2003, a revised version was published as *Haskell 98 Language and Libraries: The Revised Report*.
[src:curry-language/haskell] The language continues to evolve rapidly, with the Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC) implementation representing the current *de facto* standard.
[src:curry-language/haskell] In early 2006, the process of defining a successor to the Haskell 98 standard, informally named *Haskell Prime*, began.
[src:curry-language/haskell] This was intended to be an ongoing incremental process to revise the language definition, producing a new revision up to once per year.
[src:curry-language/haskell] The first revision, named *Haskell 2010*, was announced in November 2009 and published in July 2010.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Haskell 2010 added several well-used and uncontroversial features previously enabled via compiler-specific flags.
[src:curry-language/haskell] The next formal specification had been planned for 2020.
[src:curry-language/haskell] On 29 October 2021, with GHC version 9.2.1, the GHC2021 extension was released.
[src:curry-language/haskell] While this is not a formal language spec, it combines several stable, widely used GHC extensions to Haskell 2010.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Haskell features lazy evaluation, lambda expressions, pattern matching, list comprehension, type classes and type polymorphism.
[src:curry-language/haskell] It is a purely functional programming language, which means that functions generally have no side effects.
[src:curry-language/haskell] A distinct construct exists to represent side effects, orthogonal to the type of functions.
[src:curry-language/haskell] A pure function can return a side effect that is subsequently executed, modeling the impure functions of other languages.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Haskell has a strong, static type system based on Hindley–Milner type inference.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Its principal innovation in this area is type classes, originally conceived as a principled way to add overloading to the language, but since finding many more uses.
[src:curry-language/haskell] The construct that represents side effects is an example of a monad: a general framework which can model various computations such as error handling, nondeterminism, parsing and software transactional memory.
[src:curry-language/haskell] They are defined as ordinary datatypes, but Haskell provides some syntactic sugar for their use.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Haskell has an open, published specification, and multiple implementations exist.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Its main implementation, the Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC), is both an interpreter and native-code compiler that runs on most platforms.
[src:curry-language/haskell] GHC is noted for its rich type system incorporating recent innovations such as generalized algebraic data types and type families.
[src:curry-language/haskell] The Computer Language Benchmarks Game also highlights its high-performance implementation of concurrency and parallelism.
[src:curry-language/haskell] An active, growing community exists around the language, and more than 5,400 third-party open-source libraries and tools are available in the online package repository *Hackage*.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Using Haskell's Fixed-point combinator allows this function to be written without any explicit recursion.
[src:curry-language/haskell] As the *Integer* type has arbitrary-precision, this code will compute values such as `factorial 100000` (a 456,574-digit number), with no loss of precision.
[src:curry-language/haskell] All listed implementations are distributed under open source licenses.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Jan-Willem Maessen, in 2002, and Simon Peyton Jones, in 2003, discussed problems associated with lazy evaluation while also acknowledging the theoretical motives for it.
[src:curry-language/haskell] In addition to purely practical considerations such as improved performance, they note that lazy evaluation makes it more difficult for programmers to reason about the performance of their code (particularly its space use).
[src:curry-language/haskell] In particular it disables type classes by default.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Ben Lippmeier designed Disciple as a strict-by-default (lazy by explicit annotation) dialect of Haskell with a type-and-effect system, to address Haskell's difficulties in reasoning about lazy evaluation and in using traditional data structures such as mutable arrays.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Robert Harper, one of the authors of Standard ML, has given his reasons for not using Haskell to teach introductory programming.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Among these are the difficulty of reasoning about resource use with non-strict evaluation, that lazy evaluation complicates the definition of datatypes and inductive reasoning, and the "inferiority" of Haskell's (old) class system compared to ML's module system.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Haskell's build tool, Cabal, has historically been criticized for poorly handling multiple versions of the same library, a problem known as "Cabal hell".
[src:curry-language/haskell] The Stackage server and Stack build tool were made in response to these criticisms.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Cabal has since addressed this problem by borrowing ideas from the package manager Nix, with the new approach becoming the default in 2019.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Clean is a close, slightly older relative of Haskell.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Its biggest deviation from Haskell is in the use of uniqueness types instead of monads for input/output (I/O) and side effects.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Haskell events have been regularly held concurrent with the International Conference on Functional Programming (ICFP) including workshops such as the Haskell Symposium (formerly the Haskell Workshop) and Commercial Users of Functional Programming.
[src:curry-language/haskell] Other events include the Haskell Implementors Workshop, ZuriHac in Zurich, and Hac: The Haskell Hackathon.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] In programming language theory, **lazy evaluation**, or **call-by-need**, is an evaluation strategy which delays the evaluation of an expression until its value is needed (non-strict evaluation) and which avoids repeated evaluations (by the use of sharing).
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is often combined with memoization, as described in Jon Bentley's *Writing Efficient Programs*.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] If so, the stored result is simply returned.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] If not, the function is evaluated, and another entry is added to the lookup table for reuse.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is difficult to combine with imperative features such as exception handling and input/output, because the order of operations becomes indeterminate.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] The opposite of lazy evaluation is eager evaluation, sometimes known as strict evaluation.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Eager evaluation is the evaluation strategy employed in most programming languages.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation was introduced for lambda calculus by Christopher Wadsworth.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] For programming languages, it was independently introduced by Peter Henderson and James H.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Delayed evaluation is used particularly in functional programming languages.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] When using delayed evaluation, an expression is not evaluated as soon as it gets bound to a variable, but when the evaluator is forced to produce the expression's value.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is fundamental in big data frameworks such as Apache Spark, where computations on distributed datasets are delayed until results are explicitly needed, allowing for execution optimizations and reduction of unnecessary processing.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation allows control structures to be defined normally, and not as primitives or compile-time techniques.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] These have the usual semantics, i.e., `ifThenElse a b c` evaluates (a), then if and only if (a) evaluates to true does it evaluate (b), otherwise it evaluates (c).
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] That is, exactly one of (b) or (c) will be evaluated.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Similarly, for `EasilyComputed || LotsOfWork`, if the easy part gives **True** the lots of work expression could be avoided.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Finally, when evaluating `SafeToTry && Expression`, if *SafeToTry* is **false** there will be no attempt at evaluating the *Expression*.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Conversely, in an eager language the above definition for `ifThenElse a b c` would evaluate (a), (b), and (c) regardless of the value of (a).
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] This is not the desired behavior, as (b) or (c) may have side effects, take a long time to compute, or throw errors.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] It is usually possible to introduce user-defined lazy control structures in eager languages as functions, though they may depart from the language's syntax for eager evaluation: Often the involved code bodies need to be wrapped in a function value, so that they are executed only when called.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Delayed evaluation has the advantage of being able to create calculable infinite lists without infinite loops or size matters interfering in computation.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] The actual values are only computed when needed.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] For example, one could create a function that creates an infinite list (often called a *stream*) of Fibonacci numbers.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] The calculation of the *n*-th Fibonacci number would be merely the extraction of that element from the infinite list, forcing the evaluation of only the first n members of the list.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] In the function numberFromInfiniteList, the value of infinity is an infinite range, but until an actual value (or more specifically, a specific value at a certain index) is needed, the list is not evaluated, and even then, it is only evaluated as needed (i.e., only to the desired index).
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Provided the programmer is careful, the program completes normally.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] In Haskell syntax, "`:`" prepends an element to a list, `tail` returns a list without its first element, and `zipWith` uses a specified function (in this case addition) to combine corresponding elements of two lists to produce a third.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] In computer windowing systems, the painting of information to the screen is driven by *expose events* which drive the display code at the last possible moment.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] By doing this, windowing systems avoid computing unnecessary display content updates.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Another example of laziness in modern computer systems is copy-on-write page allocation or demand paging, where memory is allocated only when a value stored in that memory is changed.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Laziness can be useful for high performance scenarios.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] An example is the Unix mmap function, which provides *demand driven* loading of pages from disk, so that only those pages actually touched are loaded into memory, and unneeded memory is not allocated.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] MATLAB implements *copy on edit*, where arrays which are copied have their actual memory storage replicated only when their content is changed, possibly leading to an *out of memory* error when updating an element afterwards instead of during the copy operation.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] The number of beta reductions to reduce a lambda term with call-by-need is not larger than the number needed by call-by-value or call-by-name reduction.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Call-by-need embodies two optimizations - never repeat work (similar to call-by-value), and never perform unnecessary work (similar to call-by-name).
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation can also lead to reduction in memory footprint, since values are created when needed.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] In practice, lazy evaluation may cause significant performance issues compared to eager evaluation.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] For example, on modern computer architectures, delaying a computation and performing it later is slower than performing it immediately .
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] This can be alleviated through strictness analysis.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation can also introduce memory leaks due to unevaluated expressions.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Some programming languages delay evaluation of expressions by default, and some others provide functions or special syntax to delay evaluation.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] In KRC, Miranda, and Haskell, evaluation of function arguments is delayed by default.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] In many other languages, evaluation can be delayed by explicitly suspending the computation using special syntax (as with Scheme's "`delay`" and "`force`" and OCaml's "`lazy`" and "`Lazy.force`") or, more generally, by wrapping the expression in a thunk.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] In lazy programming languages such as Haskell, although the default is to evaluate expressions only when they are demanded, it is possible in some cases to make code more eager—or conversely, to make it more lazy again after it has been made more eager.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] This can be done by explicitly coding something which forces evaluation (which may make the code more eager) or avoiding such code (which may make the code more lazy).
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] *Strict* evaluation usually implies eagerness, but they are technically different concepts.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] However, there is an optimisation implemented in some compilers called strictness analysis, which, in some cases, allows the compiler to infer that a value will always be used.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] In such cases, this may render the programmer's choice of whether to force that particular value or not, irrelevant, because strictness analysis will force strict evaluation.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] In Haskell, marking constructor fields strict means that their values will always be demanded immediately.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] The `seq` function can also be used to demand a value immediately and then pass it on, which is useful if a constructor field should generally be lazy.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] However, neither of these techniques implements *recursive* strictness—for that, a function called `deepSeq` was invented.
[src:curry-language/lazy-evaluation] Also, pattern matching in Haskell 98 is strict by default, so the `~` qualifier has to be used to make it lazy.
